# Issue Title

Strange Behaviour with returning json. Properties are missing in ActionResult Ok() method, when they was defined inside a parent interface. Problem seems with inheritance of Interfaces only.

I have a object that uses an interface which uses another "parent"-interface. I initialize a new object , set all properties, and all properties can be seen via inspecting variables like expected. But the Endpoint isn't returning the property from parent-interface, only using properties defined inside children interface.


# General
Using
  * C#
  * VS 2019 16.3.2
  * .Net Core SDK 3.0.100

Problem occurs after upgrading from .Net Core 2.1 to .Net Core 3.0. Using .Net 2.1 it was working. 

I have a ASP.Net Core REST endpoint, which return a json in the format:

### Exptected response Datatype (from Swagger):
```
{
  "data": [
    {
      "posts": 0,
      "refCount": 0,
      "onBlacklist": true,
      "name": "string"
    }
  ]
}
```

### What I actually got as response **(missing name property)**:
```
"data": [
    {
      "posts": 123,
      "refCount": 456,
      "onBlacklist": false
      // missing name property here!
    }
]
```

### What I expected as reponse **(with name property)**:
```
"data": [
    {
      "name": "someName",
      "posts": 123,
      "refCount": 456,
      "onBlacklist": false
    }
]
```

### To Reproduce

```
    public interface ISomeRandomTag : ITag
    {
        int Posts { get; set; }
        int RefCount { get; set; }
        bool OnBlacklist { get; set; }
    }

    public interface ITag
    {
        string Name { get; set; }
    }

    public class SomeRandomTag : ISomeRandomTag 
    {
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public int Posts { get; set; }
        public int RefCount { get; set; }
        public bool OnBlacklist { get; set; }
    }

    public IActionResult SomeEndpoint() {
        var someRandomTag  = this.SomeHelperMethod();
        var output = new Dictionary<string, ISomeRandomTag>();
        output.Add("data", someRandomTag);
        Console.WriteLine(output);         // <--- or via Breakpoint to display that "name" is set
        return this.Ok(output);               // <--- "name" property is missing at endpoint response
    }

    private ISomeRandomTag SomeHelperMethod() {
            return  new SomeRandomTag
            {
                  Name = "test",
                  Posts = 123,
                  RefCount = 456,
                  OnBlacklist = false
            };
    }

```

# Solution / Workaround

I figured out, overriding the property from parent class and define it again with `new` solves the problem:

```
    public interface ISomeRandomTag : ITag
    {
        int Posts { get; set; }
        int RefCount { get; set; }
        bool OnBlacklist { get; set; }
        new string Name { get; set; }        // <---- adding this solves the problem
    }

```

Hope I could write it understand-able. Looking forward to solve it. If you guys aren't able to reproduce, I can check if I can setup a reproduce-able project.

